{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"286da814-4009-4f61-b555-5422b6cc9da2","content":"Yes, you'll hit **framework compatibility issues**. MSTest v3 dropped support for end-of-life runtimes. Here's how your targets are affected:\n\n| Target | MSTest v3 Support |\n|---|---|\n| `net462` | ✅ Supported |\n| `netcoreapp3.1` | ❌ Dropped (EOL) |\n| `net5.0` | ❌ Dropped (EOL) |\n\n**To migrate**, you'd need to update your unsupported TFMs to supported ones (e.g., `net6.0` or `net8.0`). MSTest v3 supports **.NET Framework 4.6.2+** and **.NET 6.0+**.\n\nAdditionally, MSTest v3 introduces a unified `MSTest` package replacing the separate `MSTest.TestFramework` and `MSTest.TestAdapter` references, and has some breaking API changes (e.g., around `ClassInitialize`/`ClassCleanup` inheritance behavior).\n\nWould you like me to update the project file for MSTest v3?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3c31e382-ffb6-402b-ab65-c71b79678eed","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user's project targets `net5.0`, `net462`, and `netcoreapp3.1`. They want to migrate to MSTest v3.\n\nMSTest v3 has some important compatibility changes:\n\n1. **Dropped framework support**: MSTest v3 drops support for older target frameworks. Specifically:\n   - `.NET 5.0` is no longer supported (it's out of support from Microsoft)\n   - `.NET Core 3.1` is no longer supported (also out of support)\n   - `.NET Framework 4.6.2` — I need to check this. MSTest v3 requires at minimum .NET Framework 4.6.2, so `net462` should still be supported. Actually, let me reconsider. \n\nSo MSTest v3 supports .NET Framework 4.6.2 and .NET 6.0 and later, which means the migration will require dropping support for `netcoreapp3.1` and `net5.0` since both are out of support anyway. The `net462` target should remain compatible.\n\nThe package structure has also changed—MSTest v3 recommends using the unified `MSTest` meta-package instead of managing `MSTest.TestFramework` and `MSTest.TestAdapter` separately, though the individual packages still work. Beyond that, there are several breaking changes like modified `Assert.ThrowsException` behavior and inheritance changes for `ClassInitialize`/`ClassCleanup`, but the real blocker is the target framework incompatibility.","outputTokens":766,"requestId":"041A:18C0B2:164613F:17B8F29:6A033805"},"id":"ae0d6af3-af3e-4b22-bee7-7cc2377849fd","timestamp":"2026-05-12T14:24:27.436Z","parentId":"bee81cbf-866d-43d6-9cff-16ec288648f9"}
